  <walkingDescription><![CDATA[<p>The Canadian Rockies are renowned as a destination for hikers. The backcountry scenery from the network of more than 4,000km of marked trails is remarkable, giving you first hand views of sparkling lakes and glaciers, waterfalls and ancient forests. Wherever you stay you’ll find a multitude of hiking options on your doorstep.</p>
<p><strong>From Banff<br /></strong>Bow Falls, Tunnel Mountain and the Marsh Trail are some of the favourite walks from Banff.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>From Lake Louise<br /></strong>Diverse trails for various abilities lead from the village, with serene strolls along the Plain of Six Glaciers and wonderful walks up to the picturesque Lake Agnes tea house. The Bow Summit and Lake, and Moraine Lake and the Valley of the Ten Peaks are other walks from Lake Louise, and this is good hiking territory where you can challenge yourself in the dazzling scenery of the Larch and Paradise valleys.</p>
<p><strong>From Jasper<br /></strong>You can enjoy a leisurely walk on one of the many trails that surround the friendly, laid back little frontier town of Jasper. The Old Fort Point, Annette Lake and the Maligne Canyon and Lake are all good walks from here, and hikes to Edith Cavell meadows are popular too.</p>
<p> </p>]]></walkingDescription>
